    rationale: "In-laboratory PSG is the gold standard and is specifically required when significant comorbidities (such as severe heart failure, COPD, or neuromuscular disease) complicate interpretation. Heart failure can cause central apneas (Cheyne-Stokes respiration) that HST cannot reliably distinguish from obstructive events because HST lacks EEG and does not measure respiratory effort adequately. HST (A) is appropriate only for high-risk patients without significant comorbidities. Pulse oximetry alone (C) is insufficient for diagnosis. Empiric CPAP (D) without diagnosis is not standard care.",
    metadata: { topic: "polysomnography", priority: "high" },
